Bug: this process is primarily a Model Context Protocol server speaking JSON-RPC over stdio. At startup it ALSO starts an HTTP SSE server for optional task streaming. Symptom: if the SSE port is already in use, the ENTIRE process dies with an uncaught error + stack trace on stderr — taking down the stdio MCP server, which doesn't need that port at all. Desired: if SSE can't bind, the stdio MCP server should keep running normally (SSE just unavailable) and the failure should be logged usefully. Diagnose and fix. (Also: we'd like the bind port to be injectable so tests can use an ephemeral port.)

streaming/sse-server.ts:
```ts
import http from "node:http";
import { logger } from "../logger.js";

const SSE_PORT = parseInt(process.env["SSE_PORT"] ?? "3001", 10);

export function startSseServer(taskStore: TaskStore): http.Server {
    const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
        // ... routes GET /tasks/:id/stream, subscribes to the event bus, writes SSE frames ...
    });

    const SSE_HOST = process.env["SSE_HOST"] ?? "127.0.0.1";
    server.listen(SSE_PORT, SSE_HOST, () => {
        logger.info({ host: SSE_HOST, port: SSE_PORT }, "SSE server listening");
    });

    return server;
}
```

index.ts uses it synchronously and closes it on shutdown:
```ts
const sseServer = startSseServer(taskStore);
// ... later, on shutdown:
await new Promise<void>((resolve) => sseServer.close(() => resolve()));
```
